AGI - The director of the Islamic and Arab Studies Center of the State University of San Diego (Sdsu), Ahmet T. Kuru, published an analysis in which he investigates motivations, backgrounds and possible political implications of the incarceration of the mayor of Istanbul, Ekrem Imamoglu, which took place at the early hours of dawn yesterday. The detention as an instrument of censorship of oppositions, recalls the polythologist on the site of deepening The Conversation, is not a novelty in Turkey.
&nbsp;
Selahattin Demirtas, the former pro-curd party leader Democratic People's Party, has been in jail for over eight years with accusations of terrorism; and Umit Ozdag, leader of the Victory Party, far right, has been in prison for two months for insulting Erdogan and incited to hatred. Although they were uncomfortable figures for the power of Erdogan, neither of them constituted a real threat, while Imamoglu has, according to the teacher, a wide appeal between different electoral blocks, succeeding in attracting the Kurdish vote while maintaining strong links with nationalist politicians thanks to his charism and his oratory.
&nbsp;
Moreover, the first citizen of Istanbul is considered a candidate who can join secular and Islamic voters, showing admiration for the founder of the Republic, secular and nationalist, Kamal Ataturk but reciting, at the same time, verses of the Koran in public.
&nbsp;
This ability to federate different political opinions helped Imamoglu defeat the Erdogan party in Istanbul twice in 2019 - after the first defeat, Erdogan refused to accept the result and the Supreme Election Council cancelled the election. Imamoglu's re-election as mayor in 2024 consolidated his reputation as a leading politician capable of defeating Erdogan at the polls.
&nbsp;
Already the Turkish municipal elections of 2024 marked a change in internal politics, with the Chp of which is part Imamoglu which exceeded the Akp of Erdogan for the first time since 2002, obtaining both the major city, Istanbul, and the capital Ankara. The threat became more pressing, in the eyes of the Turkish president, on the eve of the primaries of the party of Imamoglu, the Chp, which were scheduled on March 23.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
In this frame is inserted the arrest of yesterday and, even before, the withdrawal of the degree of Imamoglu: a diploma that dated over 30 years and whose annulment would prevent him from applying, since according to the Turkish constitution it is a necessary requirement to run for the presidency. But the accusations against Imamoglu, is always Kuru's opinion, would be moved by an even more ambitious goal: prevent him from covering any public assignment.
&nbsp;
In an apparent attempt to neutralize the threat posed by the mayor five months after the 2023 presidential elections, a court had sentenced Imamoglu to 2 and a half years of prison for insulting public officials, after defining "stupid" members of the Supreme Electoral Council of Turkey.
&nbsp;
The decision is now under appeal and, if confirmed, would prevent Imamoglu from holding public posts, including the role of mayor. This would give a triple victory for Erdogan: he would be able to resume the office of mayor of Istanbul appointing an official chosen by him, would push for constitutional modifications intimidating the MPs and eliminate his stronger rival from any future presidential race.
&nbsp;
The professor of political science also recalls the recent history of the Chp, where a weak leadership, would be fundamental to the consolidation of the power of Erdogan; For 20 years, Kemal Kilicdaroglu's leadership has accumulated defeats in presidential, parliamentary and municipal elections.
&nbsp;
An important factor in the decline in the popularity of Erdogan and his party is the economic crisis. Since 2022, Turkey's annual inflation rate has remained around 50%, eroding purchasing power and causing a significant migration of the most qualified Turks.&nbsp;
